President Obama hosted the first-ever White House Maker Faire, where he met with students, entrepreneurs, and everyday citizens who are using new tools and techniques to launch businesses, learn vital skills in science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM), and lead a grassroots renaissance in American manufacturing. The President announced new steps the Administration and its partners are taking to increase access to tools and techniques and to bring ideas to life. Efforts include helping makers launch new businesses and create jobs, expanding the number of students that have the opportunity to become makers, and challenging makers to tackle pressing problems. The President also announced partnerships with federal agencies and companies to support maker-led startups, provide mentorship for startups, and provide support for makers in schools and libraries. Additionally, various private sector companies and organizations announced initiatives to support makers, such as creating maker spaces, providing funding and resources, and launching mentorship programs.